    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="bibliography" subtype="edition">
                <p>First published, with French translation, in <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:finot-1904d"/>: <biblScope>928</biblScope></bibl>; whence, with significantly improved translation into English, in <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:majumdar-1927"/>: <biblScope>27</biblScope></bibl>; whence <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:golzio-2004"/>: <biblScope>9-10</biblScope></bibl>. Re-edited from the inked EFEO estampage, with new translation, in <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:ECIC-V"/>: <biblScope><seg type="check">forthcoming</seg></biblScope></bibl>, whence the present edition.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="sa-Latn-x-CI" xml:space="preserve" rend="break-verse-lines">
            <ab><lb n="1"/>
               <g type="siddham"/></ab>
            <lg met="Anuṣṭubh" n="I">
               <l>maheśvarasakhasyedaṃ kuverasya dhanākaraṃ</l>
               <l>prakāśadharmmanṛpatiḥ pūjāsthānam akalpayat·</l>
            </lg>
            <lg met="Anuṣṭubh" n="II">
               <l><lb n="2"/>ekākṣapiṅgalety eṣa devyā darśśanadūṣitaḥ</l>
               <l>saṃvarddhayatv īśadhanaṃ pāyāc cāhitatas sadā <pc>||</pc></l>
            </lg>
         </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <ab>
                    <app loc="IIb">
                        <lem>darśśanadūṣitaḥ</lem>
                        <rdg resp="Finot">darśanadūṣitaḥ</rdg>
                        <note>In conformity with his general practice, Finot here applies silent normalization.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="IId">
                        <lem>||</lem>
                        <rdg resp="Finot"><space/></rdg>
                    </app> 
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>I. The king Prakāśadharman has fashioned [this] place of worship, a mine of riches, for Maheśvara's (i.e. Śiva's) companion Kubera.</p>
                <p>II. Spoiled in [one] eye by the goddess, [such that he became known] as Ekākṣapiṅgala, may he cause the property of the Lord to increase, and may he always protect from what is untoward (<foreign>ahitataḥ</foreign>).’
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="fr">
                <p>We cite Finot's translation of 1904:</p>
                <p>Ce sanctuaire du compagnon de Maheśvara, Kuvera, mine de richesses, le roi <sic>Prakāśadharma</sic> l'a édifié. Si quelqu'un est affligé d'une maladie d'yeux par la déesse Ekākṣapiṅgalā (la rousse borgne), qu'il augmente les richesses du Seigneur, et (celui-ci) le défendra du mal à jamais.</p>
                            </div> 
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>An early version of the myth of Kubera's companionship of Śiva is recounted in the <ref>old Skandapurāṇa</ref>, at 29.169 (see <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:SP2A"/>)</bibl>.</p>
                <p>Finot understood <foreign>ekākṣapiṅgalety</foreign> as <foreign>ekākṣapiṅgalā ity</foreign> and noted that the (feminine) evil spirit Ekākṣapiṅgalā was not known to him from any other source. As was seen by Majumdar, it has to be understood as <foreign>ekākṣapiṅgala ity</foreign>, and so the name in question is (masculine) Ekākṣapiṅgala, which is a name of Kubera, e.g. in the <seg type="check"><bibl><ref>Himavatkhaṇḍa</ref> (19.4)</bibl></seg>. He appears as Ekākṣipiṅgala in the <bibl><ref>old Skandapurāṇa</ref> (29.149)</bibl>. That is also the form of the name in <bibl><ref>Rāmāyaṇa</ref> <seg type="check">7.13:24,30-31</seg></bibl>, which perhaps gives the earliest known version of the myth. For Vettam Mani's version of the myth, see <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:mani-1975"/>, § 13, <hi rend="italic">s.v.</hi> Kubera</bibl>.
                    <!-- I find it in an unpubished ancient Śaiva text, in verse 1.125 of the Guhyasūtra of the <ref>Niśvāsatattvasaṃhitā</ref>. But the context there does seem to throw any light on the present inscription.--> 
                    The sandhi is a bit unusual, but parallels can nevertheless be cited: the Cambodian
                    inscription K. 524, st. I, begins with <foreign>vidyāvāseti nāmāhaṃ tejasvī bhuvi viśrutaḥ</foreign>
                    (<bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:coedes-1937-1966"/> III, p. 134</bibl>); the second half of <seg type="check"><bibl><ref>Harivaṃśa</ref> 12.16</bibl></seg>: <foreign>yathotpannas tathaivāhaṃ
                    kumāra iti viddhi mām | tasmāt sanatkumāreti nāmaitan me pratiṣṭhitam ||</foreign>.
                    Our interpretation of the two modal verbs in the second stanza as both being predicates to a single subject (<foreign>eṣa</foreign>) disagrees with Finot's, following instead Majumdar's. The latter scholar has still misunderstood the significance of <foreign>darśanadūṣita</foreign>, for based on the myth to which allusion is made here, this must clearly mean an impairment <hi rend="italic">at</hi> the eye (of Kubera), rather than <hi rend="italic">by</hi> the eye (of the Goddess).</p>
                <p>By contrast with Majumdar, who translates <quote>the wealth of this king</quote>, we consider it likely that <foreign>īśadhana</foreign> here denotes primarly the wealth of Śiva (<foreign>devadravya</foreign>) endowed to his temple, and that a subsidiary shrine to Kubera was installed near it for protective purposes.
                    <!-- previously, we had this paragraph as follows: -->
 <!-- We consider it most likely that <foreign>īśadhana</foreign> here denotes the wealth of Śiva, called Maheśvara in st. I. We cite from unpublished notes of Alexis Sanderson: <quote>Majumdar understands 'the Lord' here to be the King. But this would be acceptable only if there were an insurmountable obstacle to taking the word in its primary sense as a reference to Śiva. I see no such obstacle. On the contrary I see a good reason to understand the primary sense, namely that the inscription concerns a treasury attached to a temple of Śiva. The wealth to be increased must that of Śiva himself (<foreign>devadravyam</foreign>) in the form of his temple's endowment and the income therefrom administered on his behalf.</quote> -->
                </p>
            </div>
